ResourceHeader.ResourceName: SOLO Energetic Particle Detector, SupraThermal Electrons and Protons (EPD-STEP) Main Product, Level 2 (L2), Data

RevisionEvent.Note: Initial release of metadata, ADAPT generated, LFB

ResourceHeader.Description: Energetic Particle Detector (EPD). Instrument suite, part of the scientific payload aboard the Solar Orbiter mission, dedicated to the study of solar energetic particles. EPD measures electrons, protons and heavy ions with high temporal resolution over a wide energy range, from suprathermal energies to several hundreds of MeV/nucleon. It is composed of four units: SupraThermal Electrons and Protons (STEP), Electron Proton Telescope (EPT), Suprathermal Ion Spectrograph (SIS) and High Energy Telescope (HET). https://doi.org/10.1051/0004-6361/201935287

Parameter.Name: Epoch
Parameter.Description: Nanoseconds since J2000
Parameter.Caveats: Start of acquisition interval. Variable cadence: 10 s in far mode, 1 s in close mode

Parameter.Name: Delta epoch
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: EPOCH
Parameter.Description: Accumulation period in seconds

Parameter.Name: Quality flag
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: EPOCH
Parameter.Description: Data quality flag
Parameter.Caveats: 0:Bad, 1:Known problems, 2:Survey data, 3:Good, 4:Excellent

Parameter.Name: Quality bitmask
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: EPOCH
Parameter.Description: Computer readable quality parameter
Parameter.Caveats: 0x1: Bad value, 0x2: Close mode, 0x4: High flux mode, 0x8: Stray light problems, 0x10: Large detector dead times, 0x20: Detector saturation

Parameter.Name: Small pixels flag
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: EPOCH
Parameter.Description: Flag indicating when small pixels are used (0: Regular pixels, 1: Small pixels)
Parameter.Caveats: Small pixels are used for reducing the geometry factor of the detector in periods with very high particle flux.

Parameter.Name: Integral Background Count Rate
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: EPOCH
Parameter.Description: Count rate in the background pixel (0) for the integral channel
Parameter.Caveats: Count rate measured by the background pixel (0) on the integral channel. This pixel is shielded to prevent particles from the nominal field of view from reaching the detector, but it is still susceptible to highly energetic particles penetrating the housing and passive parts of the sensor. It can be used to get a rough estimation of the background signal in the other pixels, which are currently not corrected for this effect

Parameter.Name: Magnet Background Count Rate
Parameter.Set: Time series defined by using: EPOCH
Parameter.Description: Count rate in the background pixel (0) for the magnet channel
Parameter.Caveats: Count rate measured by the background pixel (0) on the magnet channel. This pixel is shielded to prevent particles from the nominal field of view from reaching the detector, but it is still susceptible to highly energetic particles penetrating the housing and passive parts of the sensor. Parameter.Name: Pixel 1 Elec. Flux Multiplier
Parameter.Description: Conversion factors for computing electron intensities from integral-magnet flux excess for pixel 1
Parameter.Caveats: Electron intensity in pixel 1 can be obtained as Electron_Flux_01_Mult * ( Integral_01_Flux - Magnet_Flux_01 ). The result gives the intensities in the energy channels given in the variables Electron_Bins_*. This factor is calculated as the ratio between the product of the geometric factor and the bin width for protons and those for electrons. During periods with poor electron count statistics, this operation may lead to negative values. Although negative intensities have no physical meaning by themselves, they should be used when performing time or energy averages in order to get the correct results.

Parameter.Caveats: Electron intensity in pixel 12 can be obtained as Electron_Flux_12_Mult * ( Integral_12_Flux - Magnet_Flux_12 ). The result gives the intensities in the energy channels given in the variables Electron_Bins_*. This factor is calculated as the ratio between the product of the geometric factor and the bin width for protons and those for electrons. During periods with poor electron count statistics, this operation may lead to negative values. Although negative intensities have no physical meaning by themselves, they should be used when performing time or energy averages in order to get the correct results.
